## 0.3.0 — USN Journal Support

Add NTFS USN (Update Sequence Number) journal reading for incremental file index updates. This is the complement to MFT scanning: MFT gives the full snapshot, USN journal gives the delta since last scan.

### Why

file-wizard currently re-scans the entire MFT on every run. On a drive with 12M+ records this takes seconds for the MFT read but minutes for the content dedup pass. With USN journal support, file-wizard can detect only what changed since the last scan and update its index incrementally.

### Scope

- Read USN journal entries from a volume handle (native C++ read via `FSCTL_READ_USN_JOURNAL`)
- Return structured records: file reference number, parent reference number, reason flags (create/delete/rename/modify), timestamp, filename
- Map USN records back to `MftRecord` via record numbers for path resolution
- Track journal cursor (USN ID + next USN) so callers can resume from where they left off
- Expose as `MftVolume.ReadUsnJournal(sinceUsn)` or similar

### Design Notes

- Reuses the existing volume handle from `MftVolume.Open()`
- Native layer already has buffer management infrastructure — USN reads use similar double-buffered pattern
- Journal entries reference MFT record numbers, so consumers will typically pair this with a cached MFT index
- Requires admin elevation (same as MFT scanning)

## Review Follow-Ups

- Add tests that exercise the public API directly for the path-aware surface.
  Address by adding coverage for `ReadAllRecords(resolvePaths: true)` and `FindRecords(...)` semantics.

- Decide whether `MFTLib` should expose a higher-level scan-result contract for app-to-helper transport.
  Address by evaluating whether downstream apps should keep custom text formats for elevated scans or share a library-owned record serializer.

- Optional: make benchmark environment failures explicit instead of silently printing `Unknown`.
  Address by logging the WMI/CIM exception message or HRESULT in the benchmark header when system info queries fail.
